'''Russkaya Arktika National Park''' ({{lang-ru|<U+041D><U+0430><U+0446><U+0438><U+043E><U+043D><U+0430><U+043B><U+044C><U+043D><U+044B><U+0439> <U+043F><U+0430><U+0440><U+043A> "<U+0420><U+0443><U+0441><U+0441><U+043A><U+0430><U+044F> <U+0410><U+0440><U+043A><U+0442><U+0438><U+043A><U+0430>"}}) is a [[national park]] of [[Russia]], which was established in June 2009.  It covers a large and remote area of the [[Arctic Ocean]] and the northern part of [[Novaya Zemlya]] ([[Severny Island]]).

==Geography==

As of 2009 the total area of the national park is 14,260 sq km, including 6,320 sq km on the land and 7,940 sq km of the Arctic Ocean.<ref name="nenetsk">{{cite web | date = 2009-06-17 | url = http://www.adm-nao.ru/?show=news&id=2460&PHPSESSID=9aa7498197d970c343758afd1e269f8d | title = <U+041D><U+0430><U+0446><U+0438><U+043E><U+043D><U+0430><U+043B><U+044C><U+043D><U+044B><U+0439> <U+043F><U+0430><U+0440><U+043A> <U+00AB><U+0420><U+0443><U+0441><U+0441><U+043A><U+0430><U+044F> <U+0410><U+0440><U+043A><U+0442><U+0438><U+043A><U+0430><U+00BB>| publisher = <U+0410><U+0434><U+043C><U+0438><U+043D><U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+0440><U+0430><U+0446><U+0438><U+044F> <U+041D><U+0435><U+043D><U+0435><U+0446><U+043A><U+043E><U+0433><U+043E> <U+0430><U+0432><U+0442><U+043E><U+043D><U+043E><U+043C><U+043D><U+043E><U+0433><U+043E> <U+043E><U+043A><U+0440><U+0443><U+0433><U+0430> | accessdate = 22 <U+0438><U+044E><U+043D><U+044F> 2009 |language = Russian}}</ref>

The area is the habitat of [[polar bear]]s and [[bowhead whale]]s.  The area also includes one of the largest bird colonies in the [[Northern Hemisphere]], as well as [[walrus]] and [[Pinniped|seal]] [[rookery|rookeries]].<ref name="nenetsk"/>  In addition to preserving natural habitats, the area of the national park is important for preserving the cultural heritage, which is related to the history of discovery and colonisation of the vast Arctic territories starting from the sixteenth century.<ref name="nenetsk"/>

== History ==
The Russian government first established the Franz Joseph Land Conservation Area on 23 April 1994.<ref name="strf">{{cite web | date = 2009-06-15 | url = http://www.strf.ru/science.aspx?CatalogId=222&d_no=20934/rus/europe_square.htm | title = <U+0423><U+0447><U+0440><U+0435><U+0436><U+0434><U+0451><U+043D> <U+043D><U+0430><U+0446><U+0438><U+043E><U+043D><U+0430><U+043B><U+044C><U+043D><U+044B><U+0439> <U+043F><U+0430><U+0440><U+043A> <U+00AB><U+0420><U+0443><U+0441><U+0441><U+043A><U+0430><U+044F> <U+0410><U+0440><U+043A><U+0442><U+0438><U+043A><U+0430><U+00BB>| publisher = <U+041D><U+0430><U+0443><U+043A><U+0430> <U+0438> <U+0442><U+0435><U+0445><U+043D><U+043E><U+043B><U+043E><U+0433><U+0438><U+0438> <U+0420><U+043E><U+0441><U+0441><U+0438><U+0438> | accessdate = 2009-06-22 |language = Russian}}</ref> The intention to create a national park was announced in 2008.  On 15 June 2009 [[Vladimir Putin]] signed the decree establishing the park.<ref name="strf"/>  Announcing the event Putin expressed his hopes that the National Park could help develop tourism in the area.  He also announced plans to spend his vacations in the newly established national park.<ref name="rbc">{{cite web | date = 2009-06-22 | url = http://www.peopleandplanet.net/doc.php?id=3587 | title = New Russian Arctic Park to protect key polar bear habitat | publisher = People & the Planet  | accessdate = 2009-06-23}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

